Generating useful features for further analysis on Amazon reviews

Introduction

Business Context. You are a business consultant with new clients that are interested in analyzing reviews of their products on Amazon (as opposed to Yelp). They want to answer business questions like: "What are the most important factors driving negative reviews?", "Have there been any large changes to customer satisfaction/reviews over time?", etc.

Business Problem. Your main task is to explore the given data and use the results of your investigation to engineer relevant features that could facilitate subsequent analysis and model-building.

Analytical Context. The dataset provided is a large body of reviews related to movies and television left on Amazon between 1996 and 2014. When exploring our dataset, we will quickly encounter a familiar problem we discussed in the previous case: the word "good" is one of the most important words in both positive and negative reviews. Thus, we must develop methods to put "good" in the appropriate context.

Loading the data

We use a dataset of around 37,000 video reviews from Amazon Instant Video and 1,700,000 movie and TV reviews, all obtained from the website: http://jmcauley.ucsd.edu/data/amazon/. Note that there are much larger datasets available at the same site. We can expect better and more consistent results on larger datasets (such as book reviews). Note that these datasets are compressed (gzipped), and they are in JSON format, with each line representing a review and each line being its own JSON object.

We begin by loading the dataset below:

Examining the data

We take a look at the first 5 rows of each dataset to see what attributes are available. These are

  • reviewerID: A unique ID to identify the author of the review.
  • asin: The "Amazon Standard Identification Number" which provides more information about the exact product and version.
  • reviewerName: The username chosen by the reviewer.
  • helpful: A record of how many users indicated that the review was helpful/not helpful.
  • reviewText: The full text of the review.
  • overall: The overall rating (1-5) left by the reviewer.
  • summary: A short version of the review, used as the title.
  • unixReviewTime: The date that the review was created, in Unix Epoch format.
  • reviewTime: A human readable date giving the day, month, and year.

def composedHistogram(data, varList):
  fig = plt.figure(figsize=(6,5))
  for i, var in enumerate(varList):
      plt.subplot(2,2,i+1)
      sns.distplot(data[var], kde=False)
      plt.title("Histogram of " + var)
  fig.set_tight_layout(True)
  plt.close()
  return fig

def calculateLenghts(data):
  data['nChar'] = data['reviewText'].apply(lambda x: len(x))
  data['nWords'] = data['words'].apply(lambda x: len(x))
  data['nSent'] = data['sentences'].apply(lambda x: len(x))

def summaryTime(data, timePeriod):
  data1 = data\
  .set_index('datetime')\
  .to_period(timePeriod)\
  .groupby('datetime')\
  .mean()
  return data1

Therefore, the latter is a bit more predictable, and likewise an increase in favorability is observed since 2013 on both platforms, although the effect is more noticeable for the platform of Movies and TV.

def tableMonthYear(data, var):
  data1 = data\
  .groupby(['year', 'month'])[var]\
  .sum().reset_index()\
  .pivot(index='month', columns='year', values=var)
  return data1

fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize=(15,8), sharey=False, sharex=True)

tableMonthYear(movies_tv, 'nWords').plot(marker = 'o', grid=True, cmap='Blues', ax = ax[0][0], legend=False)
tableMonthYear(movies_tv, 'nSent').plot(marker = 'o', grid=True, cmap='Blues', ax = ax[1][0], legend=False)
tableMonthYear(instant_video, 'nWords').plot(marker = 'o', grid=True, cmap='Oranges', ax = ax[0][1], legend=False)
tableMonthYear(instant_video, 'nSent').plot(marker = 'o', grid=True, cmap='Oranges', ax = ax[1][1], legend=False)
ax[0][0].set(xlabel='Month', ylabel='No. Words', title = 'Movies & TV Reviews')

ax[1][0].set(xlabel='Month', ylabel='No. Sentences')

In the composite graph of the size of the reviews, it is observed that the reviews on the Instant Video Platform are greater than those shown on the Movies and TV Platform for the three size indicators (No. characters, No. words and No. sentences).

In the graph by year, it is observed that the size of the reviews began to increase from 1998 with a maximum in 2004, and since then it has begun to decrease for both platforms.

In a graph disaggregated by month and year, it is observed that there are a few months in which quite high reviews were elaborated for the Instant Video Platform compared to the Movies and TV Platform. In this composite graph, the decrease in the size of the reviews from 2013 is evident. This indicates that users have lost interest in expressing their comments on the quality of the service in recent years of the data sets.

The last graph allows a better view of the behavior per month, it is observed that for both platforms in the first years there were not such large reviews, but over the years the size of the reviews has increased. The reviews are a little more detailed in the months of January, December and October, it is possible that this coincides with the months of highest consumption of the service.

def searchGoodMoreOneByIndex(x):
  keyList = [i[0] for i in x]
  try:
    positionGood = keyList.index('good')        # Position of word 'Good'
    x1 = x[positionGood + 1]                    # Returns a Word
  except:
    x1 = 'None'
  return x1

def selectFirstWordAfterGood(data):

    data[(data['overall'] <3) &
         (data['clean_words'].map(lambda x: 'good' in x))]
  .head(10)['clean_words']

  return result

    positionGood = keyList.index('good')                                # Position of word 'Good'

from nltk.util import ngrams
In [159]:
def columnwithNgrams(data, n, k):
  dummy = data.map(lambda x: [i for i in x if not re.match(r'[^\w\d\s]', i)])
  dummy = dummy.map(lambda x: [' '.join(i) for i in (ngrams(x, n))])
  most_common_k = Counter([i for j in dummy for i in j]).most_common(k)
  return most_common_k
# dummy =columnwithNgrams(movies_tv['clean_words'], 2, 10)

def summaryPlotGram(data, n, k, color, ax):
  du = columnwithNgrams(data, n, k)
  df = pd.DataFrame({'Gram': dict(du).keys(), 'Count':map(int, dict(du).values())})
  df = df.sort_values('Count')
  plot = df.plot.barh(x='Gram', y='Count', color=color, ax=ax)
  return plot

With trigrams more interesting patterns begin to appear, for example in good reviews there are "one best movies", "films ever made", "movies ever made", "one favorite movies", while in bad reviews there is "one worst movies "," worst movies ever "," can't believe "," really wanted like "," can't imagine "and even some titles" Texas Chainsaw Massacre ". With tetragrams, the differences between good reviews ("best movies ever made", "one best films ever") and bad reviews ("one worst movies ever", "minor spoiles necessary solely", "HATE MOVIE HATE MOVIE" ).

Exercise 6:

Throughout the above search for informative words, we have seen that unigrams are not enough, but important words (such as "good") are not always next to the informative words that they describe. Devise a method to extract these informative words. Provide a brief description of how you will extract the informative words.

Answer.

The informative words for this case are adjectives since they provide a qualification of the objects, these words usually refer to nouns, but as they are mentioned they are not always close to the noun to which they are named. We must use a strategy that allows us to find the closest nouns to your adjective. A tagging strategy can be used with a vector search, an example of the process is provided in the extractAdjectiveNounPair() function.

Exercise 7:

Write a function(s) that transforms a sentence into a new text list by iteratively pairing each adjective in the sentence with the next noun that follows it in the sentence. For example, the text "That was a good, long movie" should return ["good movie", "long movie"].

Answer.

In [164]:
def extractAdjectiveNounPair(data):
  # Data is a list with words
  # Perform tagging of each words, then select pairs (key and value) that are Nouns or Adjectives
  d = [(key,val) for key,val in nltk.pos_tag(data) if val in ['NN', 'NNS', 'NNP', 'NNPS', 'JJ', 'JJR', 'JJS']]
  # Select only adjective values from d - these are the first thing we are going to look for
  dA = [(key,val) for key,val in d if val in ['JJ', 'JJR', 'JJS']]
  # Return a vector of positions of the adjectives from 'd' (tagged words)
  pos = [[key for (key, val) in d].index(i) for (i,j) in dA]
  # 
  pairs = []                                # Create an empty list
  # 
  for i,(key, val) in enumerate(dA):
    # This select the tuple that contains the adjective
    adjective = d[pos[i]][0]
    # This list contains all words as tuple list till the position and then filter only nouns (result a list of nouns)
    # Select the last one
    try:
      list1 = [i for i,j in d[pos[i]:] if j in ['NN', 'NNS', 'NNP', 'NNPS']][0]
    except:
      list1 = '-' # In cases were there is an adjectives without posterior nouns 
    # 
    p = adjective + " " + list1           # Concatenation of adjective and noun
    pairs.append(p)                         # Extension of list

  return pairs

def summaryPlotQualifier(data, k, color, ax):
  du = Counter([i for j in data for i in j]).most_common(k)
  df = pd.DataFrame({'Qualifier': dict(du).keys(), 'Count':map(int, dict(du).values())})
  df = df.sort_values('Count')
  plot = df.plot.barh(x='Qualifier', y='Count', color=color, ax=ax)
  return plot
